(5565, 11, 'Cleaning-disinfecting holding pens : short-term optimization of procedures and mid-to-long-term solutions', 'The aim of this study was to validate the effectiveness of daily cleaning-disinfecting and to test the effectiveness of using a wetting agent before the prewash and the method for applying the detergent (spray or foam-delivered). Time recordings and water consumption measurements were used to gauge feasibility for industrial scale application. Four protocols were tested: using or not using a wetting agent, high-pressure prewashing, power-spraying, then spray-delivery or foam-delivery disinfection. One slaughterhouse gave poor total bacterial flora results due to wear and tear of the wall coatings in the holding pens. Using a wetting agent did not lead to more effective cleaning-disinfection of the bays. It proved more effective to use a foam-delivered disinfectant than a spray-delivered disinfectant, particularly on the walls.\r\nUsing a wetting agent did not cut down the cleaning time required. Using the foam-delivery solution made it easier to see which surfaces had been cleaned, while at the same time offering a longer disinfectant contact time. Cleaning-disinfecting of holding pens is one of the links in the pork industryâ€™s salmonella control chain. Automated cleaning facilities and a parallel circuit for jet-spray delivery of the disinfectant are solutions that should be considered.', 'Le Roux A;Minvielle B;Gault E;', 'Vol.31 1', 1201820400, '', '990', 'nettoyage;dÃ©sinfection;porcherie d''attente;agent mouillant;salmonelle;prÃ©lavage', '', '', '', 'n', '', 'o'),
