(5415, 11, 'Incorporation of 10% rapeseed meal in gestating diet colza and impact on farrowing performance', 'Two gestating diets were formulated on a similar net energy (9.01 MJ/kg) and digestible amino acids contents (lysine : 5.0 g/kg) basis. In diet COLZA, 10% rapeseed meal, 11% pea and 19% sugar beet pulp were incorporated whereas no rapeseed meal nor pea and only 7% of sugar beet pulp were used in diet CONTROL. Other feed materials used were wheat, barley, soybean and sunflower meals, which contents differed among diets.\r\nBody condition of sow at farrowing was similar for both diets. No difference was observed on litter size which is consistent with a maximum intake of 2.5 mmoles of glucosinolates per day, i.e. less than the maximum amount recommended (5 mmoles/d).', 'Quiniou N;', 'Vol.29 4', 0, '2006  juillet-aoÃ»t', '839', 'alimentation;colza;gestation;mise bas;performances;tourteau de colza;', '', '', '', 'n', '', 'o'),
(5416, 11, 'Pig production processed and marketed on-farm; part 2: factors governing economic profitability', 'The aim of this article is to propose economic profitability indicators to help farmers understand their activity,\r\nidentify improvements or develop new projects.\r\nThe farm-type system developed based on the economic profitability of farms surveyed enables any pig barn that processes and sells its products on-farm to position itself in relation to operating surplus per kg carcass and compare to sector characteristics.\r\nThis comparison should enable the farm manager to identify criteria where this is room for improvement.', 'Frotin P;Gerault C;BouyssiÃ¨re M;Minvielle B;', 'Vol.29 4', 0, '2006  juillet-aoÃ»t', '840', 'porcs;rentabilitÃ©;transformation Ã  la ferme;Ã©conomie;', '', '', '', 'n', '', 'o'),
(5414, 11, 'When to board porkers onto the farm-based loading station ? Impact on carcass performance, stomach weight and meat quality, and yield when processing as hams', 'Boarding pigs onto the loading station 1 hr after the last meal has significant effects on carcass performance when outside temperatures are high, regardless of whether the pigs are wet-fed or feeder-fed. Stomach weights recorded at the slaughterhouse show little variation in relation to station loading hour. Stomach weights recorded at slaughter 24 hours after the last meal are more likely to vary in relation to feed system than the time at which the pigs boarded the loading station. In general, meat quality criteria (pH and colour) showed no significant variation. A mock-up of processing as hams highlighted that loading one hour after the last meal has a negative effect on slicing and technological performance. This finding remains to be confirmed in a larger sample population. Generally speaking, it would appear preferable to load pigs onto the loading station at least 7 hours after the last feed.', 'Chevillon P;Vautier A;Gault E;', 'Vol.29 4', 0, '2006  juillet-aoÃ»t', '838', 'carcasse;embarquement;jambon;jambons;local d''embarquement;porcs;porcs charcutiers;qualitÃ©;qualitÃ© de la viande;transformation;viande;', '', '', '', 'n', '', 'o'),
