(5225, 11, 'Euthanasia in pig farming', 'In a pig farming context, given the efficacy, feasibility and cost of the various methods tested, the recommended\r\nmethod for piglets over 8 kg, porkers and breeding animals is now the â€œMatadorâ€-type captive bolt pistol. This technique causes immediate loss of consciousness together with lethal irreversible brain injury. For piglets less than 8 kg, when a captive bolt pistol with appropriate bolt length and cartridge is not available, the most efficient method is stunning by a blow to the head. This method is quick and effective.', 'Chevillon P;Mircovich C;Dubroca S;FlÃ©ho JY;', 'Vol.27 4', 0, '2004  juillet-aoÃ»t', '649', 'bien Ãªtre;euthanasie;', '', '', '', 'n', '', 'o'),
(5224, 11, 'Testing of pig respiratory lesions at the slaughterhouse. Relevance in farm monitoring and practical application', 'Slaughterhouse testing has many objectives:\r\nAt farm level, the tests can detect or confirm disease while orienting the diagnosis. The tests provide strong indicators of health status across a group of farms. They can also be used in experimental research.\r\nThe reliability of the results obtained depends both on the quality of the readings taken and the relevance of the monitoring\r\nplan. It is therefore important to use standardised rating methods and to take the sampling scheme into account when interpreting the results.', 'CorrÃ©gÃ© I;', 'Vol.27 4', 0, '2004  juillet-aoÃ»t', '648', 'contrÃ´le Ã  l''abattoir;lÃ©sions pulmonaires;poumons;sanitaire;', '', '', '', 'n', '', 'o'),
