(5213, 11, 'Economic incidence of high prolificacy in pig herds: comparison of 13 scenarios', 'As the litter size increased, the number of weaned piglets per litter also grew up but slowlier in connection with the higher proportion of undersized animals (weighing less than 1 kg at birth) and the high perinatal mortality. Different adaptations for herd management were assessed. In the farrowing unit, piglets were assumed either to stay all with their dam or to be early weaned for some of them. At 8 or 25 kg, the required additional facilities could be built, piglets in excess could be sold or fattened under contract in a third farm. The number of sows was either kept constant or reduced. New accommodation investment costs and labour costs were taken into account. Technical performances were assumed to be the same, either the sows were hyperprolific or not. Keeping all piglets with their dam, building extra places or making some pigs to be fattened out of the farm, appeared like the most worthwhile scenario. Although reducing the number of sows increased the margin, it represents one of the less profitable solutions. The improvement of little piglets survival allowed to fatten more pigs within interesting economic conditions.', 'Gourmelen C;Le Moan L;', 'Vol.27 3', 0, '2004  mai-juin', '637', 'hyperprolificitÃ©;prolificitÃ©;reproduction;Ã©conomie;', '', '', '', 'n', '', 'o'),
(5214, 11, 'Impact of the 2003 heat wave on milking and reproductive performance at the ITP station', 'When the ambient temperature continuously exceeds 25Â°C, the resulting heat stress causes a fall in milk production\r\nand feed consumption in reproducer sows that is detrimental to lactation and even to reproduction. The situation is\r\neven worse when the temperature is constantly above 27Â°C. Such conditions were observed during summer 2003, in\r\nparticular during the heat wave in the first half of August.', 'Quiniou N;Boulot S;Bartolomeu D;Morvan R;', 'Vol.27 3', 0, '2004  mai-juin', '638', 'canicule;lactation;logement;performances;performances de lactation;performances de reproduction;reproduction;RomillÃ©;', '', '', '', 'n', '', 'o'),
(5208, 11, 'Additives using in piggeries : effects on odour and ammonia in finishing rooms', 'Concerning efficiency of commercial additives in the reduction of odour and ammonia in finishing pig units, a study was carried out by the three partners (Chambres dâ€™Agriculture des Pays de la Loire et de la VendÃ©e et ITP) in five commercial pig units. Measurements of odours and ammonia were achieved during cold and hot period including the season effect. Results of this study show a small effect of commercial products on ammonia reduction (around 20 %) with a great variation linked to the season. Concerning odour reduction, effect of the season on additiveâ€™s efficiency was very important. In general, reduction of odour emission was more important in hot period, which is a good thing because of the increase of outdoor activities and then conflicts between neighbourhood and breeders during this period.', 'Guingand N;Boulestreau AL;Juin S;Maupertuis F;', 'Vol.27 2', 0, '2004  mars-avril', '632', 'additifs;ammoniac;engraissement;environnement;odeurs;Ã©missions;', '', '', '', 'n', '', 'o'),
(5209, 46, '', '', 'Calvar C;Quiniou N;', 'Vol. 22', 0, '2004  mai', '633', 'acides aminÃ©s;lactation;porcelet;truie en lactation;truies;', '', '', '', 'n', '', 'o'),
(5207, 11, 'Destructured meat in the pork industry : combined effects of transport and resting time before slaughter on the frequency of the appearance of this defect', 'In this study, the frequency of destructured ham was very low, less than 5 % of the 1126 deboned hams were concerned by this defect, and only 1.5 % of the hams were severely or totally destructured (scores 3 and 4). When the period of fasting was constant, the frequency of the defect was significantly effected by transport time. There was no effect of resting time at the slaughterhouse on the frequency of the defect. Despite the low incidence of the defect, our results confirmed that destructured hams had a lower pH and paler colour. The results confirmed that destructured meat was associated with heavier hams and leaner and heavier carcasses. The influence of transport time on the frequency of destructuration can be explained by differences in ultimate pH (24 h). Indeed, when the length of the fasting period is constant, a longer transport time induces greater glycogen consumption, which results in a higher ultimate pH.', 'Vautier A;Minvielle B;Boulard J;Houix Y;', 'Vol.27 2', 1078095600, '', '631', 'viandes dÃ©structurÃ©e', '', '', '', 'n', '', 'o'),
(5205, 11, 'Deck height and ventilation for transport times of less than eight hours', 'In summer the height of the fully opened side shutters allows rapid air change during transport and limits the deterioration of ambient air conditions during stops. In winter partial covering or closure of the shutters on the left side reduces the air flow rate to one third and limits air speed among the pigs. Deck height is not the only criterion that needs to be considered to ensure air change and air quality conducive to the welfare of the pigs. The height of the side shutters and the total opened surface area on both sides of each deck are most important and so have also to be taken into account.\r\nAdequate ventilation of the pigs by fully opening the shutters can be supplemented by spraying the pigs in the truck.\r\nAdditional fan ventilation is thus superfluous for transport less than 8 hours. In summer natural ventilation through\r\nopened side shutters is optimal Deck height in three-deck trucks can be between 85 and 95 cm.', 'Chevillon P;Frotin P;Rousseau P;', 'Vol.27 2', 0, '2004  mars-avril', '629', 'aÃ©ration;bien Ãªtre;camions de transport;transport;ventilation;', '', '', '', 'n', '', 'o'),
