(5127, 11, 'I & R: The pig traceability system in the Netherlands', 'After the outbreak of classical swine plague in 1997, and in response to European Directives, the Netherlands have put in place an I & R system to record and monitor the movement of pigs in the country.\r\nIn this country all piglets are identified within one week of weaning by means of ear tags marked with the farm number (UBN No.) and a serial number. Before being taken for slaughter, porkers and cull breeders are re-identified by a metal tag marked with an individual number that is noted on the docket kept in the slaughterhouse records. Two sorts of notification of movement are made in the I & R database: one by the farm of origin and one by the processor on arrival. The Dutch I & R traceability system is designed to ensure protection against further disease outbreaks and act as a consumer guarantee.', 'Dagorn J;', 'Vol.26 4', 0, '2003  juillet-aoÃ»t', '551', 'base de donnÃ©es;contraintes rÃ©glementaires;enregistrement;identification;Pays Bas;Ã©conomie;', '', '', '', 'n', '', 'o'),
(5124, 11, 'Farming under environmental constraints in France, Denmark, the Netherlands and Spain', 'Northern European countries are subject to strict regulations concerning farming in general, and these rules set limits for the activities of farmers. Even so, in the Netherlands the reduction of production is not yet complete. In Spain there is room for new developments. In France, pig production is experiencing severe difficulties.', 'Daridan D;Van Ferneij JP;Rieu M;Chevrant Breton A;', 'Vol.26 4', 0, '2003  juillet-aoÃ»t', '548', 'contraintes rÃ©glementaires;Danemark;environnement;Espagne;France;Pays Bas;Ã©conomie;', '', '', '', 'n', '', 'o'),
(5125, 11, 'Pig farmers processing and marketing their pigs : Review of surveys and technical diagnosis', 'This review was made between July 2000 and December 2001. It shows the diversity and complexity of pig farms where the pigs produced on the farm are (totally or partially) processed and marketed. Common characteristics and several groups emerge according to the orientation and the size of the processing facility or the number of pigs commercialised and marketed. The most useful criterion for characterising pig farms engaged in processing and marketing is the percentage of pigs processed relative to the number of pigs produced. As regards profitability, knowledge of the economic characteristics of these farms deserves further study. These data should be collected regionally or locally, and then centralised. Common characteristics could then be extracted and true references established beyond local specific features.', 'Minvielle B;BouyssiÃ¨re M;BouldÃ© B;', 'Vol.26 4', 0, '2003  juillet-aoÃ»t', '549', 'diagnostic;dÃ©marches qualitÃ©;enquÃªte;guide de bonnes pratiques;transformation Ã  la ferme;', '', '', '', 'n', '', 'o'),
