(4747, 11, '', '', 'Marouby H;', 'Vol.25 4', 0, '2002', '165', 'abattage;bilan annuel;France;qualitÃ© technologique;Ã©conomie;', '', '', '', 'n', '', 'o'),
(4742, 11, '', '', 'Marouby H;Van Ferneij JP;', 'Vol.25 3', 0, '2002', '160', 'Europe;prix;prix du porc;production;UE;Union EuropÃ©enne;Ã©conomie;Ã©volution;', '', '', '', 'n', '', 'o'),
(4743, 11, 'Impact of housing on the welfare of the growing pig', 'The establishment of the social hierarchy within a group of pigs is achieved through numerous aggressive acts. Improvements in pen design or environmental enrichment appear to be less effective in limiting the\r\naggression observed when pigs are grouped together, than simply reducing the number of times pigs of different origins are brought together. Limited pen-space per animal lead to more frequent aggressive interactions\r\nbetween pigs and both limited and excessive pen-space lead to a decrease in growth rate. Floor type, as well as the thermal environment, play a role in thermoregulatory activity. The presence of straw can\r\ndiversify exploratory activity. The experiments required to study this subject need to integrate pen-space, group size and feasibility. This importance of environmental consequences should not be forgotten.', 'Courboulay V;Rousseau P;Meunier-SalaÃ¼n MC;', 'Vol.25 3', 0, '2002', '161', 'bien Ãªtre;logement;porcs charcutiers;', '', '', '', 'n', '', 'o'),
(4744, 11, 'Salmonella in pig farms : characterisation and epidemiological importance of the Salmonella status of gilts', 'The salmonella status of gilts (assessed individually and in groups) at the beginning of quarantine, as well as the evolution during quarantine were investigated by bacteriological culture of faeces and serological detection of serum antibodies against salmonella by an ELISA test. The results of the two techniques often\r\ndisagreed and this made it difficult to choose a method with which to characterise the level of salmonella infection of a group of animals and even more so for a single animal. During quarantine a significant proportion of groups of gilts showed seroconversion. The most frequently detected serovars were S. derby and S. typhimurium. Based on the present results (frequency of isolation, serovar identification, serological status), obtained in supplier herds and in herds where the gilts will be used, the level of salmonella infection of a herd is not linked to the level of infection of its gilts, at the beginning and end of quarantine, nor the level of infection of the supplier herd.', 'CorrÃ©gÃ© I;', 'Vol.25 3', 0, '2002', '162', 'cochette;salmonelles;sanitaire;Ã©pidÃ©miologie;', '', '', '', 'n', '', 'o'),
(4745, 11, 'Appraisal of acid-base equilibrium in pigs and electrolytic status of feed', 'Pig feed tends to contain less and less protein-rich raw materials, owing to the increased availability of industrial amino acids. This principle of formulation yields feeds whose electrolytic status needs to be\r\nchecked and corrected if necessary, so that minimum requirements are guaranteed for each animal growth stage.', 'Quiniou N;', 'Vol.25 3', 0, '2002', '163', 'alimentation;aliments;bilan;Ã©lectrolyse;Ã©quilibre acido-basique;', '', '', '', 'n', '', 'o'),
(4738, 11, 'Growth performance, carcass and meat quality of four local breeds', 'This study confirms the poor fattening performance of local breeds compared with improved breeds.\r\nOnly the Blanc de lâ€™Ouest pig stands out by its zootechnical performance, which lies between the three other local breeds and the Large White. This inferiority is further worsened by poorer reproductive performance,\r\nwhere the Blanc de lâ€™Ouest again has an intermediate rank. For these reasons these animals can only be exploited outside the mainline industry. Extensive finishing has proved highly detrimental to growth performance and feeding efficiency. However, the carcasses obtained are leaner. In conclusion, the utility of extensive finishing resides mainly in the reduced fatness it induces, which enhances the visual\r\nappeal of the produce.', 'GuÃ©blez R;Labroue F;Mercat MJ;', 'Vol.25 2', 0, '2002', '156', 'croissance;gÃ©nÃ©tique;performances;races locales;viande;', '', '', '', 'n', '', 'o'),
(4739, 11, 'Quality labels in pig production', 'Today more than 80% of pigs are produced under quality labels. All these guarantee at least the origin of the produce and its traceability, and some a mode of production. In France the VPF label groups various quality and controlled origin systems under a single logo.', 'De JubÃ©court D;', 'Vol.25 2', 0, '2002', '157', 'production;signes de qualitÃ©;', '', '', '', 'n', '', 'o'),
(4740, 11, '', '', 'Guingand N;', 'Vol.25 2', 0, '2002', '158', 'ammoniac;convention de GenÃ¨ve;environnement;loi sur l''air;', '', '', '', 'n', '', 'o'),
(4741, 11, 'Salmonella contamination of butchery pig transport vehicles and holding pens at slaughterhouses', 'All butchery pig transport vehicles and nearly half the alleys of holding pens at slaughterhouses are contaminated with Salmonella after use. They are therefore potential sources of Salmonella contamination for healthy animals. Truck cleaning-disinfecting procedures that are effective against Salmonella and compatible\r\nwith the activities of drivers have been defined. Their application after every slaughterhouse delivery prevents cross-contamination between batches. For holding pens at slaughterhouses suitable cleaning-disinfecting procedures remain to be specified. They could be applied daily or after every at-risk delivery.', 'Rossel R;Le Roux A;Minvielle B;', 'Vol.25 2', 0, '2002', '159', 'abattoir;camions de transport;contamination;porcs charcutiers;salmonelles;transport;', '', '', '', 'n', '', 'o'),
(4734, 11, 'Detailed chemical composition of pig feed and manure.', 'The analysis of the composition of pig manure for 22 elements enabled us to quantify its fertilising potential and toxicity hazards for the quantities usually spread. On the basis of 170 kg of nitrogen per hectare the input was approximately 100 kg of P2O5, 170 kg of K2O, 140 kg de CaO, 50 kg of SO3, 35 kg of MgO and Na2O, which compensated for all or part of the nutrients lost in harvested crops or through leaching.\r\nThe manure also helps provide trace elements that may be deficient, such as iron, boron, copper, zinc, molybdenum and manganese.', 'Levasseur P;', 'Vol.25 1', 0, '2002', '152', 'aliments;composition chimique;environnement;lisier;', '', '', '', 'n', '', 'o'),
(4735, 11, 'Factors involved in introducting sows', 'There is a consensus on the importance of introducing sows for maintaining healthy livestock. Introducing sows requires defining the health status of the sows and expectancies.\r\nThe health status of the receiving herd must not be forgotten.\r\nThe successful outcome of introducing sows relies on good husbandry and management of quarantine.', 'CorrÃ©gÃ© I;', 'Vol.25 1', 0, '2002', '153', 'introduction des reproducteurs;reproducteurs;sanitaire;', '', '', '', 'n', '', 'o'),
(4732, 11, 'Tail docking and teeth cutting in piglets. Behavioural, zootechnical and health consequences', 'artial cutting of teeth in piglets (to prevent wounding of piglets and the udders of sows) and tail docking (to prevent tail biting) have lately been challenged. A behavioural, zootechnical and health analysis helped to improve knowledge of the consequences of these practices. The study suggested disturbances in the animalâ€™s behaviour that could be associated with a temporarily stressful situation.\r\nThe effects of teeth cutting on behaviour and skin wounds in piglets were moderate. However, clipping teeth reduced growth rate in animals in the first week of life. Tail docking caused short-term reactions that\r\nsuggested pain, but had no long-term consequences on behaviour, wounding or growth of piglets.', 'Bataille G;Rugraff Y;Chevillon P;Meunier-SalaÃ¼n MC;', 'Vol.25 1', 0, '2002', '150', 'bien Ãªtre;caudectomie;porcelet;sanitaire;section des dents;', '', '', '', 'n', '', 'o'),
